<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note5" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5</A>
Herter, <I>Rhein. Mus.</I>, 78 (1929), p366, takes <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">centum</SPAN> with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">divae</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note6" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">6</A>
With lines 24‑60, 75‑94, on hunting-nets, <I>cf.</I> Xen. <I>Cyn.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.3‑8; Arrian, <I>Cyn.</I> 1;
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/onomasticon01polluoft#page/n355/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pollux, <I>Onomast.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.26‑32</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/Cynegetica/1*.html#ref58
	"TARGET="Oppian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusG,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Oppian, <I>Cyn.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.150‑51</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Nemesianus/Cynegetica*.html#299
	"TARGET="Nemesianus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nemes. <I>Cyn.</I> 299 <I>sqq.</I>
	</A>
The Latin <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">rete</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">δίκτυον</SPAN>) means net in general, or specifically a large "hay"; <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">plaga</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἐνόδιον</SPAN>) means a net placed in the known run or track of the game; <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cassis</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἄρκυς</SPAN>) means a funnel-shaped net resembling,
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/onomasticon01polluoft#page/n357/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
according to Pollux</A>,<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('V.31',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> a <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">κεκρύφαλος</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">reticulum</SPAN>) — which may be applied either to a network cap for the hair or to the bag-shaped reticule, pouch or belly of a hunting-net.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note7" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Limbus</SPAN>, the rope along the edge of the net, corresponds to the <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τόνος</SPAN> in Xen. <I>Cyn.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">X</SPAN>.2,
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/onomasticon01polluoft#page/n355/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pollux <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.27</A>. Grattius uses <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">limbi</SPAN>, the plural, for the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fila linea</SPAN> out of which the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">limbus</SPAN> is made (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Limbus grandis et capitalis linea illa est cui minores limbi quadrangulo sinuamine circumstringuntur</SPAN>, Barth).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Ingrati</SPAN> is predicative: "Thankless (<I>i.e.</I> profitless) will be the nets that demand greater expense."


