<I>i.e.</I> if the animal has already escaped and is no longer lying hidden there.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
The <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">θῶες</SPAN> of
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/Cynegetica/3*.html#336
	"TARGET="Oppian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusG,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Oppian, <I>Cyneg.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.336‑38</A>, are jackals sprung from a union of wolves with leopards. The <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">θώς</SPAN> of Aristotle is perhaps rather a civet than a jackal. Pliny,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/8*.html#123
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>.123</A>, mentions <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">thoes</SPAN> as a kind of wolf.


