"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Via</SPAN> is the method of the hunt, <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#note4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">5</A>. Johnson's <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">virum</SPAN> is attractive, "make the hunter keen."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>
The nose, chin, lower sides of the cheeks and the mid forehead of the badger (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">maeles</SPAN>) are white: the ends of the hairs on the body are at bottom yellowish-white, in the middle black, and at the ends ash-coloured or grey: hence the proverb "as grey as a badger." The skin dressed without removing the hair can be used for caps or pouches.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
Diana.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
Paean.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
<I>i.e.</I> he licks the wound.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
<I>i.e.</I> with the result that they rot and cause disease.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A>
With the meaning of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">amaram</SPAN> compare <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">salsa</SPAN> in 388.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A>
The goddess' name is put by metonymy for bread; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Nemesianus/Cynegetica*.html#154
	"TARGET="Nemesianus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Nemes. <I>Cyn.</I> 154</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cererem cum lacte ministra</SPAN>: so for corn,<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('American readers: not what we call corn, remember (a New World plant), but British English for any grain, usually wheat.')"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ge01.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 1<BR>of the Georgics'+Lat2+LatSearch+'rubicunda</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Virg. <I>G.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.297</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Natura_Deorum/2A*.html#60
	"TARGET="Cicero_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cic. <I>N. D.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.23.60</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_apae.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'the Aetna'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Cererem</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Aetna</I>, 10</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A>
The omission of a punctuation mark after <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">falsi</SPAN> would imply in Grattius an Epicurean disdain for primitive superstition: "those consolations of a groundless fear did not continue to command such a lasting belief." According to


<A ID="p191x"></A>the text here accepted, Grattius seems to admit that superstitious cures soothed reasonable fears, and remained long in vogue.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
The badger burrows <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground, confining itself to its hole during the day and feeding at night.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
Among prophylactic amulets the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">conchae</SPAN> were sacred to Venus. Pliny,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/32*.html#2
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XXXII</SPAN>.2‑6</A>, mentions the shell <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">echeneis</SPAN> or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">remora</SPAN>, believed to have power to stop ships by adhering to the hull. The marvellous properties of such shells, he considers, became the more credible because they were preserved and consecrated in the temple of Venus at Cnidos.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Pyrites</SPAN>: <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/36*.html#137
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Pliny, <I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XXXVI</SPAN>.137</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">molarem quidam pyriten vocant</SPAN>: <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_apae.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'the Aetna'+Lat2+LatSearch+'molarem</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Aetna</I>, 454</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἱππώνιον</SPAN> is Vibo Valentia on the Via Popilia in the territory of the Bruttii. Curcio thinks that Hippo in Numidia is meant.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Vadis</SPAN> is also explained as (1) pores (Enk), (2) intestines (Radermacher). Vollmer imagines a contrast between <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">latentibus vadis</SPAN>, meaning <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ex aquis reconditis</SPAN>, and the open sea of the next sentence.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
The Latin of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">illum mergentem</SPAN> in the sense of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">illum qui mergit</SPAN> is questionable; but <I>cf.</I> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ille . . . defecturus</SPAN>, <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#291
	"TARGET="Grattius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">291</A>. Vollmer proposes tentatively <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">illic</SPAN> or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ullum</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ira commissa</SPAN> (a curious consideration recalling <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">commissa piacula</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ae06.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 6<BR>of Vergil\'s <I>Aeneid</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'commissa</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Virg. <I>Aen.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.569</A>) is here taken with Wernsdorf to


<A ID="p195x"></A>mean <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ira quae commissis sceleribus provocata est</SPAN>. The sense is different in <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#374
	"TARGET="Grattius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">374</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Furiis commissam . . . iram</SPAN>, unless 455 can imply "in wrath assigned to him to vent."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A>
<I>e.g.</I> the oil from the bituminous lake of <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#434
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">434</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
In the form of fire and bitumen.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A>
The disease has the symptoms of tetanus according to veterinary writers: Vegetius, <I>Mulomedicina</I> 2, 88; Chiron, 315; Pelagonius, ed. Ihm, 294.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note84" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">84</A>
483‑96, description of an Ambarval sacrifice to Diana, with allusion to her worship near Aricia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note85" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref85
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">85</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Multa</SPAN>, nom. sing. fem., agreeing with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">dea</SPAN> understood: <I>i.e.</I> "in full force" (like <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">πολὺς ῥεῖ</SPAN> in Greek). Enk thinks <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">multa</SPAN> neut. plur.; Vollmer takes it for <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">mulcta</SPAN> in the sense of "mollified."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note86" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref86
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">86</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Dianae arma</SPAN> = the chase. For horses in general see Xen. <I>Cyn.</I> 1;
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/onomasticon01polluoft#page/n163/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pollux, <I>Onom.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.188 <I>sqq.</I></A>;
	<A HREF="
https://elfinspell.com/ClassicalTexts/Virgil/Mackail/Georgics-Book3.html#line72
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Virg. <I>G.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.72 <I>sqq.</I></A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Varro/de_Re_Rustica/2*.html#2.7
	"TARGET="Varro_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Varro <I>R. R.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.7</A>; Columella, <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.26‑29<!--</A>COLUMELLA6-->;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/8*.html#154
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plin. <I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>.154</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Nemesianus/Cynegetica*.html#240
	"TARGET="Nemesianus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nemes. <I>Cyn.</I> 240 <I>sqq.</I></A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/Cynegetica/1*.html#158
	"TARGET="Oppian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusG,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Oppian, <I>Cyn.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.158‑367</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note87" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref87
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">87</A>
<I>i.e.</I> at the Olympic games.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note88" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref88
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">88</A>
Syene (Assouan) in Upper Egypt below the First Cataract.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note89" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref89
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">89</A>
Taburnus was in Samnium: Garganus in Apulia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note90" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref90
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">90</A>
<I>i.e.</I> owing to the stony nature of the ground.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note91" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref91
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">91</A>
The Callaeci were a people of Hispania Tarraconensis.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note92" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">92</A>
The Nasamonian tribe dwelt in the eastern part of the Syrtis Major in N. Africa.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note93" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref93
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">93</A>
In Thrace. Grattius proceeds to express a wish that these Thracian horses could have the chance of showing their powers on the mountains of Sicily. The Sicilian horses are mentioned for their swiftness,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/Cynegetica/1*.html#fast_Sicilian_horses
	"TARGET="Oppian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusG,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Oppian, <I>Cyn.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.272</A>. Their victories in horse-racing and chariot-racing are the themes of many of Pindar's odes: <I>e.g.</I> <I>Pyth.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN> celebrates a victory won by Hieron of Aetna (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#524
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Gratt. 524</A>). Qualities of speed and surefootedness requisite in Sicilian sport (<I>cf.</I> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">qui ludus Siculis</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#525
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
525</A>, and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fragosum Nebroden</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#527
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
527‑528</A>) explained to Grattius' mind how, though not of prepossessing appearance, these


<A ID="p203x"></A>horses could be trained to win glory in the games of Greece (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cantatus Graiis Acragas</SPAN>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#527
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
527</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note94" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref94
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">94</A>
Pindar, <I>Olymp.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.2, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">κλεινὰν Ἀκραγάντα</SPAN> (= Agrigentum in Sicily, now Girgenti). <I>Olympian Odes</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN> celebrate victories won by Theron of Acragas in chariot-racing; <I>Pyth.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN> and <I>Isthm.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN> similar victories by Xenocrates of Acragas.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note95" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref95
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">95</A>
A Sicilian mountain. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Fragosum</SPAN> indicates the serviceability of Sicilian horses as hunters on rocky ground.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note96" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref96
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">96</A>
The fact that Pella was in Macedonia and the Ceraunian range in Epirus does not justify the epithet <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Pellaei</SPAN>; but, as Enk says, "poeta parum curat geographiam."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note97" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref97
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">97</A>
Cyrrha or Cirrha, a seaport in Phocia, near Parnassus on which was the Delphic oracle of Apollo.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note98" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref98
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">98</A>
A portion of the poem is lost — presumably of no great extent, as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">restat</SPAN> of <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#497
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">497
	</A>
suggests that the author was drawing to a conclusion.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Note:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:line_145_repunctuation" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#ref:line_145_repunctuation
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
Moving a (modern) comma back one word —
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Grattius/Cynegeticon*.html#145
	"TARGET="Grattius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
see the Latin
	</A>
— gives a text that makes more sense: "If something harmful damages it, the sap will flow out of these wounds and so harden the weak veins."



